<TEXT>
the number of workers employed by farmers this 
summer declined slightly from a year ago but their wages are up 
according to a quarterly survey by the agriculture department 
the survey taken last month indicated 12 million hired workers 
were employed by farmers compared with 127 million a year earlier 
those did not include 303000 agricultural service workers 
provided by crew chiefs and labor contractors a year ago 258000 
were counted 
temperatures soared to over 100 degrees throughout much of the 
nation during the survey week of july 1016 the report said 
friday 
winter wheat harvest was 82 percent complete by the weeks 
end 10 points ahead of the fiveyear average the report said 
cotton harvest was under way in the texas rio grande valley 
peach harvest was in full swing along the east coast californias 
vegetable harvest consisted mostly of broccoli cauliflower 
carrots celery melons and onions harvest of cherries 
raspberries and blueberries was active in oregon and washington 
state 
the report said the national figures for hired workers had a 
sampling error of 36 percent 
average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was 490 
per hour up 12 cents per hour from a year earlier the report 
showed 
for workers provided by contractors there was no national wage 
rage available however workers in california averaged 574 per 
hour down from 648 a year ago while those in florida received 
an average of 519 per hour up from 513 a year ago 
</TEXT>
