<TEXT>
it will be easier for military authorities to 
advise the spouses of reservists if their mates test positively for 
the deadly aids virus under new guidelines issued by deputy defense 
secretary william h taft iv 
under a 1987 policy statement if military personnel tested 
positively and agreed to provide the names of his or her sexual 
partners to medical authorities for counseling the military doctor 
could relay those names to local health officials unless prohibited 
by state law 
that policy has now been expanded to say the military doctor can 
directly contact the spouse of a reservist if that reservist has 
tested positively the spouse may then be offered aids testing and 
counseling at a military hospital or clinic taft decided even 
though the spouse of a reservist is not normally eligible for 
military health care 
the guidelines continue to allow doctors to notify spouses of 
active duty personnel 
the policy statement issued friday extends the pentagons aids 
testing program for another year continuing the mandatory blood 
screening for all military personnel on active duty all reservists 
and national guard members and all men and women seeking to join 
the armed services 
it further continues the practice of allowing military personnel 
who test positively to remain on active duty until they show signs 
of the actual disease 
however it rejects for the time being mandatory testing of 
civilian defense employees destined for overseas posts such 
civilian workers will be tested only if they are being assigned to 
a foreign country whose government requires such a test 
aids acquired immune deficiency syndrome attacks the bodys 
immune system and its ability to resist infection no cure has been 
found most of its victims are homosexuals intravenous drug users 
and people receiving tainted blood transfusions although the 
disease also is spreading through sexual contacts to the general 
population 
as of monday aids had been diagnosed in 70208 americans of 
whom more than half or 39620 have died since june 1981 according 
to the federal centers for disease control no one is known to have 
recovered from aids 
the defense department under policy statements first adopted in 
late 1985 conducts the largest aids screening program in the 
world more than 4 million individuals have been tested under the 
program which the pentagon justifies primarily on the need to 
protect military blood supplies 
the latest policy continued the practice of prohibiting any 
recruit applicant from joining the military a college rotc program 
or attending a military academy if he or she tests positively for 
aids 
</TEXT>
