<DOCNO> AP880813-0018 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
coral reefs contain a wealth of 
information on climate changes that occurred centuries ago and 
could help predict the worlds weather scientists say 
about 750 scientists from 53 nations attended a symposium on 
coral reefs that ended friday 
they also discussed the fate of coral reefs attacked by 
crownofthorns starfish that devour living coral most of the 
participants believed the reefs recover quickly but others said 
the reefs could be dead for centuries 
the most important thing to come out of the conference was the 
recognition that coral reefs are the repositories of a wealth of 
data going back millions of years said peter davies chairman of 
the symposium at james cook university 
the university is a few miles from a section of the 
1200milelong great barrier reef off australias northeastern 
coastline 
reefs have got all the data on sealevel change weather 
climate the greenhouse effect davies said 
scientists use the term greenhouse effect to refer to 
pollution that accummulates in the atmosphere and traps energy from 
the sun causing the earths temperature to rise 
davies said that scientists using such techniques as drilling 
core samples of living corals of great age could measure old 
climatic changes 
the information in the corals will let us make sensible 
predictions he said they are like a huge library it was 
reported here for the first time that we are seeing the same or 
similar structures in old corals in the sinai desert as we see in 
living corals now 
and those corals in the sinai were uplifted and exposed into 
what is now arid land 250000 years ago 
davies also said scientists are studying the biochemistry of 
corals in search of a substance that could protect humans from 
sunburn 
corals in shallow water produce a natural suncreen if they 
didnt theyd die of sunburn davies said and the research has 
a large potential 
crownofthorn starfish are found throughout the world but 
periodically they appear in vast numbers in parts of the great 
barrier reef and may destroy up to 90 percent of the coral on a 
reef 
scientists said it has not been determined why the starfish 
appear when they do and there is no known method of controlling 
them 
davies said most evidence indicates the starfish are part of the 
reef cycle and the reefs quickly recover 
but robert endean a professor at the university of queensland 
told the conference it would take centuries for large corals to 
recover and then only if the starfish did not return while they 
were regrowing 
australian scientists said they had tried injecting the starfish 
with copper sulphate catching them by hand installing underwater 
wire fences and infecting them with bacteria but nothing worked 
the scientists were told the australian armed forces once sent 
divers to kill the starfish but the cost came to about 20 per 
dead fish 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

