<TEXT>
boston is bracing for a decadelong overhaul of 
its antiquated highway system and for the headaches that will go 
with it including the possibility of a torrent of rats being 
unleashed by the big dig 
the 45 billion project includes a plan to build a third tunnel 
under boston harbor and transform the central artery interstate 93 
through downtown from a sixlane elevated highway to an eight to 
10lane underground expressway 
experts say that without the new design 14hour gridlocks could 
someday develop construction officials promise a new grander 
boston will emerge from the rubble and disarray that will begin 
affecting motorists later this year 
in place of the rusting 29yearold interstate that divides 
downtown from bostons north end and waterfront officials envision 
either a long narrow park or small controlled development above 
the underground expressway 
there will be a dramatic difference said martha bailey 
manager for environment and design for the project were giving 
the city the ability to reunite itself 
but sam wood head of the city department known as the rat 
patrol warns that the construction will destroy the habitat of 
millions of rats in underground burrows and old buildings and that 
they could overrun the city 
if someone doesnt take an aggressive stand and fight this 
with a careful program and education then its going to be a bad 
situation wood said 
in boston there is one rat for every two people a rat debacle 
occurred during construction on the southeast expressway in 1984 
when rodents overran areas like the south end section of the city 
people whisper about rats wood said they dont want to 
talk about them out loud theyre afraid of them they dont want 
to think about them 
woods inspectional services rodent control department has asked 
the state to fund a 500000 antirat plan including early baiting 
and inspection state officials are also planning to hire a rodent 
expert 
ninety percent of the staterun construction project is being 
funded by the federal highway administration 
certain expressways will be limited to one and two lanes during 
the construction worsening bostons already legendary traffic 
crunch 
to help ease the traffic the massachusetts bay transportation 
authority has been granted 3 billion to improve public 
transportation officials are hoping to persuade motorists to take 
trains buses subways and ferries to work 
according to a survey last year 39 percent of all commuters 
said they plan to change the way they get into boston and 54 
