<TEXT>
an uneasy peace long prevailed on manhattans 
lower east side an ethnic melting pot for generations while the 
dopers and drunks homeless and homesteaders yippies and yuppies 
moved in 
but then the police arrived one night and all hell broke loose 
it was like downtown beirut a store owner who spoke on 
condition of anonymity said after he watched about 400 police and 
450 protesters battle last weekend over a curfew at tompkins square 
park leaving 52 people hurt 14 of them police officers 
a week later the focus is on the actions of police more than 
80 complaints of police brutality have been filed and us 
attorney rudolph giuliani is investigating whether police violated 
the civilians civil rights 
mayor edward i koch and police commissioner benjamin ward 
initially defended police but reversed field after watching 
videotapes of officers swinging billy clubs with abandon covering 
their badge numbers and trampling people with their horses 
koch also lifted the curfew and ordered the park left open 
overnight although an 11 pm noise curfew has been enforced and 
in an effort to reduce policecivilian tensions citizen observers 
are joining officers on patrols 
the area around the park known as the east village has had 
deep divisions and frictions 
the neighborhoods mix has been heady germans ukrainians 
russians hungarians greeks poles and italians then blacks then 
hispanics and more recently indians and koreans they have been 
joined by the downandout by 60s burnouts and by upwardly mobile 
young professionals renovating old buildings 
to the west of the park are vestiges of the ukrainian and polish 
communities that once flourished coffee shops churches a 
community center clusters of elderly women speaking their native 
tongue 
along st marks place is a hippiepunk fusion vendors set up 
wares on the sidewalk in front of boutiques galleries and poster 
shops within a block you can choose from soy burgers pizza 
sushi or some sabzee chalow at an afghan place 
the riot wasnt caused by this bizarre blend but the 
neighborhood with its history of radicalism and tolerance for the 
unconventional was fertile ground for such a clash 
police said they began enforcing a 1 am curfew at the request 
of some residents who complained of noise from rowdies who hang out 
in the park which is also a drug marketplace and a dormitory for 
the homeless 
but then some witnesses said the police were greeted by a 
handful of malcontents throwing bottles 
tv stations showed videotape of the ensuing violence including 
one officer repeatedly swinging a nightstick at the man holding the 
camera 
many park regulars and poor residents believe the city and 
police are in league with real estate developers to clear the area 
of undesirables and attract more affluent tenants 
they claim abandoned buildings are left empty by landlords 
awaiting gentrification and higher rents the better ones are 
rehabilitated and filled with white uppermiddle class tenants 
they say 
its hard to say what the bigger problem is the lack of 
housing or drugs said tom brasuell 28 a lifelong resident who 
is an administrative assistant to councilwoman miriam friedlander 
poorer people are definitely getting squeezed out while people 
are doubled up in projects 
on the east side of tompkins square park the housing 
deteriorates noticeably 
walk through and you will find hundreds of buildings that have 
been vacant for the last 10 to 15 years said angel rodriguez 
who runs a youth program in the area 
but some buildings that were fixed up now offer apartments that 
rent for 1000 to 3000 a month or sell for hundreds of thousands 
of dollars 
hundreds of people live in seemingly deserted shells the legal 
ones paying the city rent while fixing up the property are 
urban homesteaders others are squatters 
theres a combination of different races and economic brackets 
in a way that is very unique said michael shenker 32 a 
composer whose homestead apartment has walls stripped to the studs 
but has electricity and a phone its something that people are 
endeavoring to maintain they dont want homogenization 
it would destroy a certain poetic quality here it would also 
mean a displacement of us thats why tempers flare its not 
about race color religion its about money 
even with socalled gentrification its still cheaper than 
the upper west side and its closer to wall street said stuart 
v rubinfield whose real estate company has been in the 
neighborhood 15 years 
but its also avantgarde this is the cutting edge of the 
art scene rubinfield said its really heterogeneous from 
the media coverage you get the idea that there are 100000 people 
in gray flannel suits invading the neighborhood its just not 
happening 
</TEXT>
