<TEXT>
irrigation has dramatically lowered the level of 
the aral sea leaving behind briny pools the size of football 
fields and 12000 square miles of land that was once under water 
pravda said saturday 
the article in the communist party newspaper written by 
geographer d oreshkin said the seas level is dropping an average 
of 3 feet annually the article blamed the problem on regional rice 
field irrigation 
the loss of the sea is a tragedy for nearby citizens the 
article said fish die and former fishermen become unemployed 
the lower levels also have seriously hampered ship deliveries of 
coal used for heating in the region the article said 
the aral sea is sometimes called a lake but it is properly a 
sea because it is a landlocked saltwater body bounded on the 
north by the soviet republic of kazakhstan and on the south by 
another soviet republic uzbekistan 
environmental problems once taboo in the official media are 
now discussed more freely under soviet leader mikhail s 
gorbachevs policy of glasnost or openness 
the topic of the ecological crisis on the aral lake was in the 
press but it looks as though action has been stopped along the 
way the pravda article said 
not only is the sea dying but peoples patience too the 
article said public opinion in areas near the aral is painfully 
concentrated on the fate of the sea all hopes are connected with 
its revival 
higher than average rainfall over the last two years alleviated 
the problem somewhat but not enough to significantly offset the 
drainage the article said it said more water was lost through 
evaporation than replenished by rainfall and the seas two main 
feeder rivers 
it said the receding aral shoreline has left pools of highly 
concentrated saltwater throughout the area some of them as big as 
football fields 
meanwhile the saline content in the ground and water near the 
lake is so high that nothing will grow the article said oreshkin 
suggested an underground drainage system to carry the saltwater 
back to the sea 
oreshkin also said irrigation water should be used more frugally 
regional farmers are dependent on irrigation of their fields of 
rice a main crop of the central asian economy 
such water problems have also been reported elsewhere 
in june the official news agency tass said authorities in 
kazakhstan the soviet republic bounding the aral sea on the north 
had halted construction of two irrigation projects for fear of 
excessively draining lake balkhash 
