<DOCNO> AP880813-0185 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the form of pneumonia that kills many 
people with aids is caused by a fungus not by microscopic animals 
called protozoa as many have assumed new studies indicate 
the discovery that pneumocystis pneumonia apparently is caused 
by a fungus could help scientists develop more effective drugs for 
treating the lung ailment said dr jeffrey c edman a researcher 
at the university of california at san francisco 
though the pneumocystis organism was discovered in the early 
1900s scientists have not known whether it is caused by a fungus 
which is a plant form or a protozoan which like a singlecell 
microbe is in the most primitive class of animals 
drugs that rely on antiprotozoan agents are being used 
effectively for treating pneumocystis but the medications such as 
pentamidine and bactrim are often accompanied by side effects 
this finding will allow us to research new areas of the 
cellular processes that are more classically associated with fungi 
and use those as guidelines for new drugs said edman 
edman said his teams findings reported in the current issue of 
the british journal nature also suggest that pneumocystis is 
acquired not from other people but from the environment such a 
finding could help doctors protect those infected with the acquired 
immune deficiency virus from getting pneumocystis 
it is not known how pneumocystis transmission occurs but its 
possible that as a fungus that it may be transmitted from somewhere 
in the environment that it may be growing somewhere we are not 
able to identify said edman 
a protozoan would likely be spread through humantoanimal 
contact or by an insect while fungi are transmitted in the 
physical environment such as in the soil 
a story in sundays editions of the new york times cited other 
doctors similar findings and quoted outside experts as agreeing 
that the findings were important for treatment of aids 
dr donald armstrong an expert in fungal diseases at memorial 
sloankettering cancer center in new york said evidence that the 
organism is a fungus will provide an impetus for scientists to 
renew their efforts to learn how we might grow it to ease 
testing of drugs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

