the nato alliance said friday it is 
committed to sharing of the costs of western defense equitably and 
to maintaining a fair partnership among the 16 member nations 
it released the statement a day after the us senate approved a 
2826 billion military spending bill including an amendment that 
suggests western europe and japan do more for their own defense 
the north atlantic treaty organization statement said equitable 
sharing of defense responsibilities concerns each ally as it is 
in the interest of all that a distribution is balanced 
there is within the alliance continuing commitment to this 
principle as well as recognition of the need to renew efforts to 
maintain under evolving circumstances a fair partnership it 
said 
there has been a growing effort in the us congress to press 
western european countries to allocate more money for defense 
congress has asked for a report by the end of this year on us 
consultations with its allies on burden sharing 
the nato statement said defense ministers have expressed their 
determination to improve collective defense and to ensure that each 
ally contributes in the most effective and equitable fashion 
a european diplomat at nato headquarters expressed concern that 
the senate measure might lead to a reduction in the us commitment 
to western europe and weaken the bargaining position at eastwest 
negotiations in vienna on reduction of conventional military forces 
in europe 
if we start reducing unilaterally then there is no point in 
the russians giving in to western pressure because there is no 
pressure said the diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the senate amendment orders a major review of us overseas 
commitments and limits the deployment of american troops in japan 
and south korea it also sets a limit on spending for us military 
personnel stationed overseas requiring the allies to pay the 
difference if deployment costs surpass 1988 levels 
a house version of the spending bill approved two months ago 
has no burdensharing amendment the measures now go to a 
housesenate conference committee 
cost sharing has been a frequent topic since nato was formed in 
1949 and there have been calls in congress in recent years to 
withdraw some of the 330000 american military personnel in europe 
nato figures show the proportional of defense spending by 
alliance members varies widely last year the united states 
budgeted 66 percent of its gross domestic product on defense while 
luxembourg provided 12 percent 
britain earmarked 49 percent in 1987 france 4 percent germany 
3 percent and canada 21 percent according to the figures 
