<DOCNO> AP880813-0205 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
babies who are bottlefed appear more likely to 
develop cancer than those who are breastfed according to findings 
published in the lancet medical journal 
the report published in the aug 13 issue and made available 
friday found that children who were artificially fed or were 
breastfed for less than six months were almost twice as much at 
risk of developing cancer before age 15 than those who were 
breastfed for more than six months 
the researchers determination of a statistical association 
between breast feeding and cancer does not prove that lack of 
breast feeding is a cause of cancer 
the report by researchers margarett k davis david a savitz 
and barry i graubard was based on a study of 201 denver children 
who developed cancer between 18 months and 15 years of age 
the researchers of the national institute of child health and 
human development in bethesda md and the university of north 
carolina at chapel hill nc studied how these children were fed 
as babies compared with how 181 healthy children were fed 
the researchers found a positive association between 
artificial feeding and childhood cancer the report said 
it said however that knowledge about childhood cancer is 
incomplete and that other variables not examined in the study may 
explain the association between artificial feeding and cancer 
it reported a possible source of bias from the parents 
inaccurate recall of breastfeeding duration after many years 
artificial feeding could deprive infants of significant 
immunological benefits which may weaken their natural defenses 
against some forms of cancer the report said 
human milk probably has antimicrobial benefits it said 
if human milk increases resistance to infection in infancy 
artificial feeding which provides no immunological benefits may 
alter the childs responses to early infection 
the interaction of the developing immune system and infectious 
agents may be critical to the individuals subsequent immune 
response to infection or reactivation of latent viral infections 
the report said 
it said the cancer most strongly associated with artificial 
feeding in the study is lymphoma 
the type of feeding also can affect other conditions later in 
life such as obesity diabetes and heart disease the report said 
the researchers said their results differed from those of 
another study by pa mckinney and associates who found no 
association between breast feeding and childhood leukemia and 
lymphoma 
the authors of the new report said their analysis of the 
duration of breast feeding was different and might account for the 
discrepancy in the results 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

