<TEXT>
they werent your ordinary runofthemill 
quarterly treasury auctions 
the federal reserves surprise hike in its key discount rate 
this past tuesday caught the bond market offguard and wreaked 
havoc on the three auctions of treasury securities that followed 
the move analysts said 
the government bonds were not well bid many foreign investors 
who play a critical role in financing the nations 25 trillion 
debt apparently were driven away from the sales 
the fed really threw the market a curve ball and did it at 
the last minute said robert brusca chief economist and senior 
vice president of the fixedincome division at nikko securities co 
international inc 
he likened the impact of the discountrate boost on the auctions 
to what godzilla did to tokyo 
the increase in the discount rate the interest the fed charges 
on loans to major financial institutions was the first such hike 
since last octobers stock market crash a rise in interest rates 
sends bond prices lower 
the central bank raised the rate a halfpercentage point to 65 
percent in order to stem inflationary pressure on the economy 
many market watchers had expected the fed to tighten its reins on 
the money supply but few were anticipating that dramatic a move 
consumers felt the ripples two days later on thursday when the 
nations major banks responded by upping their prime lending rates 
to 10 percent from 95 percent the prime rate is used as a 
benchmark for a range of loan charges for consumers and businesses 
such as home mortgage rates and credit card interest fees 
bond investors meanwhile were feeling shock waves the three 
auctions on tuesday wednesday and thursday made up the 
treasurys thirdquarter refunding aimed at raising cash to finance 
the federal debt the government sold a total 29 billion in 3year 
notes 10year notes and shortterm cash management bills 
the discountrate move and the economic uncertainty it stirred 
up couldnt have come at a worse time analysts contend 
the auction results were pretty dismal said elizabeth 
reiners a vice president at dean witter reynolds inc the demand 
that everybody had thought was out there pretty much dried up at 
the auctions 
the government issues fetched low prices driving up interest 
rates on the bonds to skyhigh levels 
