newspaper ink made from soybean oil is a runaway success but 
the high price of soybeans is likely to drive up the price of soy 
inks forcing some publishers to return to the petroleumbased 
variety 
the choice may be purely economic for large metropolitan papers 
like the boston globe which switched to soybased inks exclusively 
for its color printing work about a year ago 
but the issue could become stickier for rural newspapers in the 
farm belt where printing with soybased ink is seen as one way of 
helping the local soybean growers 
its pretty hard not to commit to the farmers here said lon 
myers director of operations for the cedar rapids gazette one of 
the first newspapers in the country to use soy ink in early 1987 
but myers said everything is subject to evaluation theres 
obviously some business judgment that has to be used 
